{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}
{{Use Canadian English|date=February 2017}} {{Italic title}} [[File:Utamaro (c. 1794–95) Kasumi-ori Musume Hinagata - Kachō (AIC).jpg|thumb|alt=|A woman peers from behind a [[mosquito net]] ]] <!-- no infobox, please --> '''''Kasumi-ori Musume Hinagata''''' ({{lang|ja|霞織娘雛形}}, "Model Young Women in Mist") is a print series by the Japanese [[ukiyo-e]] artist [[Kitagawa Utamaro]]. The theme is of beautiful women seen through different woven materials. Three prints from the series are known; whether there were more is unknown.
==Background==
[[Ukiyo-e]] art flourished in Japan during the [[Edo period]] from the 17th to 19th centuries, and took as its primary subjects [[oiran|courtesans]], [[kabuki]] actors, and others associated with the "floating world" lifestyle of the [[Yūkaku|pleasure districts]]. Alongside paintings, mass-produced [[Woodblock printing|woodblock prints]] were a major form of the genre.{{sfn|Fitzhugh|1979|p=27}} In the mid-18th century full-colour ''{{transl|ja|[[nishiki-e]]}}'' prints became common, printed using a large number of woodblocks, one for each colour.{{sfn|Kobayashi|1997|pp=80–83}} A prominent genre was ''{{transl|ja|[[bijin-ga]]}}'' ("pictures of beauties"), which depicted most often [[Oiran|courtesans]] and [[geisha]] at leisure, and promoted the entertainments of the pleasure districts.{{sfn|Harris|2011|p=60}}
[[Kitagawa Utamaro]] ({{circa|1753}}–1806) made his name in the 1790s with his ''bijin [[ōkubi-e]]'' ("large-headed pictures of beautiful women") portraits, focusing on the head and upper torso, a style others had previously employed in portraits of kabuki actors.{{sfn|Kobayashi|1997|pp=87–88}} Utamaro experimented with line, colour, and printing techniques to bring out subtle differences in the features, expressions, and backdrops of subjects from a wide variety of class and background. Utamaro's individuated beauties were in sharp contrast to the stereotyped, idealized images that had been the norm.{{sfn|Kobayashi|1997|p=88}}
{{clear}}
==Publication==
The series was published in {{circa|1794–95}} by [[Tsutaya Jūzaburō]]. It is not known how many were in the series; three are known, of which very few copies are known.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=29}} The bear the seal ''Utamaro hitsu'' ({{lang|ja|歌麿筆}}, "the brush of Utamaro").{{sfn|Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, staff}}<!-- and Tsutaya's publishing mark -->
The prints are untitled, and variations of the titles that follow exist in both English and Japanese.<!-- editor's note, not something that requires citation -->
==Description and analysis==
The series theme is of beautiful women seen through translucent woven materials.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=29}} Two women appear in each print, one in front and one behind and seen through the translucent materials.{{sfn|Yamaguchi|1991|p=85}} ''Kasumi-ori'' ({{lang|ja|霞織}}, "mist-woven") is a [[neologism]] Utamaro uses to refer to materials woven so that they can be seen through unclearly, as in a mist.{{sfn|Kobayashi|2006|p=45}} The translucent effect in the prints required the highest level of skill from their carvers{{sfn|Kobayashi|2006|p=45}} and careful moderation of the ''[[Baren (printing tool)|baren]]'' burnishing tool by the printers.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=31}}
===''Kachō''===
[[File:Utamaro (c. 1794–95) Kasumi-ori Musume Hinagata - Kachō (AIC).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=]]
In ''Kachō'' ({{lang|ja|蚊帳}}, "Mosquito net", the same characters also pronounced ''kaya''), a woman peers through a light yellowish-green{{efn|Such nets came in light yellowish green or in white.{{sfn|Yamaguchi|1991|p=142}} }} [[mosquito net]] of thin silk gauze, an item of great luxury at the time; commoners made such nets of hemp or cotton. The woman wears a in a ''{{illm|narumi shibori|ja|有松・鳴海絞り}}'' [[tie-dye]]d komono patterned with scattered circles. From above hang two ''[[hoso-obi]]'' sashes, one red and the other violet.{{sfn|Yamaguchi|1991|p=142}} This is the only print in the series in which the woman face each other;{{sfn|Yamaguchi|1991|p=142}} they appear to be in conversation.{{sfn|Yamaguchi|1991|p=142}}
{{clear}}
===''Sudare''===
[[File:Utamaro (c. 1794–95) Kasumi-ori Musume Hinagata - Sudare (MFA).jpg|thumb|upright|alt=]]
In ''Sudare'' ({{lang|ja|簾}}, "Reed screen"), woman dressed as a daughter of a high-ranking [[samurai]] family sits behind a luxurious ''[[sudare]]'' reed screen hemmed with a flower pattern. The woman who stands in front of the screen wears her hair in a {{illm|shiitake-tabo|ja|椎茸髱|lt=''shiitake-tabo''}}, a hairstyle asocciated with the women-in-waiting at high-ranked samurai homes. Utamaro has posed the women so their hairstyles contrast—the woman behind the screen's is extravagantly tied and decorated, while the woman-in waiting's is much simpler. The both have pleased, attentive expressions, and appear to be watching something—perhaps a show or presentation.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=29}}
The collectors William&nbsp;S. and John&nbsp;T. Spaulding bought a copy of this print from the architect [[Frank Lloyd Wright]] while in Japan in 1913.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=29}} The Spaulding brothers donated their copy along with the rest of their collection to the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]] on 21 December 1921.{{sfn|Museum of Fine Arts, Boston, staff}}
{{clear}}
===''Natsu Ishō''===
<!-- [[File:|thumb|upright|alt=|]] --> In ''Natsu Ishō'' ({{lang|ja|夏衣装}}, "Summer clothing"), an elegantly-dressed woman standing in the foreground holds a ''[[kanzashi]]'' hairpin with her right hand to her hair,{{sfn|Kobayashi|2006|p=45}} which is made up in a {{illm|Baimage|ja|貝髷|lt=''baimage''}} hairstyle. She appears to have just gotten out of the bath.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=31}} Another young woman looks at her from behind a translucent cloth{{sfn|Kobayashi|2006|p=45}} hung on a clothes rack. The pair appear to be in conversation.{{sfn|Fujimura|2016|p=31}}
{{clear}}
